\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 15. T. scordium} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 565 (1753). Softly hairy to subglabrous, stoloniferous perennial, smelling of garlic when crushed. Stems 10-60 cm, often freely branched. Leaves ovate to oblong, coarsely dentate, or crenate-dentate, sessile or subsessile. Flowers in the axils of leaf-like bracts which are usually longer than the flowers. Calyx villous, obscurely veined; teeth c. 1/3 as long as tube, triangular, acuminate. Corolla 7-10 mm, villous, purplish; tube slightly exceeding calyx.{\i  Wet places. Europe, northwards to Ireland, Sweden and Estonia}. All except Az Fa Fe Is No Rs (N) Sb.
